00:02:16.750 --> 00:02:18.490
for a common theme.

00:02:18.490 --> 00:02:21.520
And that is saving the ocean.

00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:25.790
The first question I
want to put forward

00:02:25.790 --> 00:02:30.630
is one that I think most
people here could relate to.

00:02:30.630 --> 00:02:33.260
What if we understood
interactions of humans

00:02:33.260 --> 00:02:34.950
with ecosystems?

00:02:34.950 --> 00:02:37.810
Humans and how they
interact with ecosystems

00:02:37.810 --> 00:02:40.930
is something that is
kind of a broad topic.

00:02:40.930 --> 00:02:43.540
When I was at Laura's
cabin in New Hampshire,

00:02:43.540 --> 00:02:47.220
we started talking about
how Google uses that term

00:02:47.220 --> 00:02:49.510
"ecosystem" and what
does that mean, and how,

00:02:49.510 --> 00:02:53.620
as a biologist, how we
use that term "ecosystem."

00:02:53.620 --> 00:02:57.960
Here's a graphic that our
Institute commissioned

00:02:57.960 --> 00:03:01.210
which is showing the
Barents Sea ecosystem.

00:03:01.210 --> 00:03:05.150
The Barents Sea is the sea
in the very north of Norway,

00:03:05.150 --> 00:03:06.707
shared with Russia.

00:03:06.707 --> 00:03:08.290
This is different
than the Bering Sea,

00:03:08.290 --> 00:03:10.210
which is off the
coast of Alaska.

00:03:10.210 --> 00:03:11.600
This is the Barents Sea.

00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:13.970
And here you see
an idealized type

00:03:13.970 --> 00:03:16.170
of picture of the ecosystem.

00:03:16.170 --> 00:03:18.470
So you have, for
example, the polar bears

00:03:18.470 --> 00:03:21.580
in the Arctic, the
big land mammals.

00:03:21.580 --> 00:03:23.080
And then you have
the ocean mammals,

00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:25.110
and then you have
the different species

00:03:25.110 --> 00:03:28.570
of fish in the different
parts of the water column.

00:03:28.570 --> 00:03:34.650
And here you have cod, the
Norwegian Northeast Atlantic

00:03:34.650 --> 00:03:37.440
cod is the largest cod
stock in the world.

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:42.680
Last year, the fishing quota
was 2.2 billion pounds,

00:03:42.680 --> 00:03:48.130
over a million metric tons,
which is a very different cod

00:03:48.130 --> 00:03:50.900
stock than the ones found off
the coast of Georges Bank here,

00:03:50.900 --> 00:03:54.790
which collapsed in the '90s and
hasn't really come back ever.

00:03:54.790 --> 00:03:58.720
So we have plenty of
fish and lots of fish

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:00.440
that we harvest in Norway.

00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:03.360
But the big question
is how we as humans

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:05.880
interact with these ecosystems.

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:07.390
When we talk about
ecosystems, we

00:04:07.390 --> 00:04:09.770
can't forget about
the human connection

00:04:09.770 --> 00:04:15.220
because humans are, in
exploited parts of the sea,

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:20.450
can be the biggest driver of
mortality in the ecosystems.

00:04:20.450 --> 00:04:22.840
So what I'm going to
talk a little bit today

00:04:22.840 --> 00:04:26.540
is I'm going to outline
the problem of how

00:04:26.540 --> 00:04:30.530
to save the ocean, how to manage
the ocean sustainably and give

00:04:30.530 --> 00:04:32.260
you a little bit of
background on that

00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:34.440
and then start looking
for some solutions,

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:37.870
some bio-socioeconomic
models that I have quantified

00:04:37.870 --> 00:04:40.690
for the Barents Sea,
the use of data,

00:04:40.690 --> 00:04:44.960
and the potential
for collaboration

00:04:44.960 --> 00:04:49.020
from government institutions
across from the politics

00:04:49.020 --> 00:04:53.680
of governments and getting
in private foundations

00:04:53.680 --> 00:04:56.750
and enterprises into the game.

00:04:56.750 --> 00:05:01.910
The issue here is, how can we
sustainably manage the ocean?

00:05:01.910 --> 00:05:04.750
And I'm going to go into
a little bit of philosophy

00:05:04.750 --> 00:05:08.070
first because I think, in
order for us to really examine

00:05:08.070 --> 00:05:10.330
the problem, it's
really nice when

00:05:10.330 --> 00:05:14.330
we can look at people who
have really examined science

00:05:14.330 --> 00:05:16.870
because that's what we're
talking about in the beginning.

00:05:16.870 --> 00:05:21.280
So I don't know if people are
familiar with the Thomas Kuhn

00:05:21.280 --> 00:05:22.630
cycle.

00:05:22.630 --> 00:05:26.780
Thomas Kuhn is a
philosopher of science.

00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:30.330
This book was
published in the 1962.

00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:32.800
And this is the Kuhn
cycle of science.

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:34.555
And this is Science
with a big S,

00:05:34.555 --> 00:05:36.900
a very generic view of science.

00:05:36.900 --> 00:05:39.020
So this can be applied
to any part of science.

00:05:39.020 --> 00:05:42.390
But when you start in the
normal science paradigm,

00:05:42.390 --> 00:05:46.940
you start with science as a
puzzle-solving entity, right?

00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:48.780
So you have problems
and you have puzzles

00:05:48.780 --> 00:05:51.060
and you're trying to solve it.

00:05:51.060 --> 00:05:56.950
In this paradigm cycle, you get
to what's called model drift.

00:05:56.950 --> 00:06:00.570
And that's when you're less
able to solve problems using

00:06:00.570 --> 00:06:04.650
the models and the
data that you have.

00:06:04.650 --> 00:06:07.210
Getting into a little
bit of French philosophy,

00:06:07.210 --> 00:06:10.600
Ivan Illich, who was
active in the 19th century,

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:14.290
has some interesting ideas
of why you would actually

00:06:14.290 --> 00:06:16.310
get model drift.

00:06:16.310 --> 00:06:18.610
There's two books that
I want to point out,

00:06:18.610 --> 00:06:21.720
"Deschooling Society" and
"Tools for Conviviality,"

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:23.010
which is really interesting.

00:06:23.010 --> 00:06:24.530
I'm just going to
put this problem

00:06:24.530 --> 00:06:27.830
that he puts forth to you.

00:06:27.830 --> 00:06:30.720
He starts out with the
institutionalization

00:06:30.720 --> 00:06:31.510
of education.

00:06:31.510 --> 00:06:34.790
We know this from centuries.

00:06:34.790 --> 00:06:37.490
We've institutionalized
how we educate people.

00:06:37.490 --> 00:06:40.990
Which gets into the
institutionalization society,

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:44.390
which gives power to
the technocratic elite.

00:06:44.390 --> 00:06:46.790
This means that if
you go to a school

00:06:46.790 --> 00:06:48.960
where you learn
certain techniques that

00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:50.690
are used for
policy, for example,

00:06:50.690 --> 00:06:53.340
this becomes a very
technocratic exercise.

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:54.770
Science becomes power.

00:06:54.770 --> 00:06:57.530
Science becomes how
we make decisions.

00:06:57.530 --> 00:07:00.060
And if you get that,
you can be stealing

00:07:00.060 --> 00:07:02.860
the power of the citizens'
practical knowledge.

00:07:02.860 --> 00:07:05.110
This becomes relevant
in resource management

00:07:05.110 --> 00:07:08.450
because, in resource management,
we deal with stakeholders.

00:07:08.450 --> 00:07:09.690
We deal with our fishermen.

00:07:09.690 --> 00:07:12.770
We deal with the
producers on shore.

00:07:12.770 --> 00:07:14.770
We deal with consumers.

00:07:14.770 --> 00:07:19.110
And this is a example of
some Florida fishermen

00:07:19.110 --> 00:07:22.350
who are protesting
some science coming

00:07:22.350 --> 00:07:24.170
from NOAA in the
recreational fisheries.

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:31.160
They're protesting that it's
a very hierarchical system.

00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:33.680
Their livelihoods are based
on the fishing quotas.

00:07:33.680 --> 00:07:36.250
The fishing quotas are based
on the stock assessments.

00:07:36.250 --> 00:07:37.880
And the stock
assessments can only

00:07:37.880 --> 00:07:41.640
be run by these technocratic
elite scientists.

00:07:41.640 --> 00:07:43.500
So this is an
interesting framing

00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:46.440
of the problem of model drift.

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:49.190
So after model drift,
we get to model crisis

00:07:49.190 --> 00:07:53.010
where we see that all of a
sudden our methods don't work.

00:07:53.010 --> 00:07:55.300
In a fisheries
prospective, this has

00:07:55.300 --> 00:07:57.940
been outlined in the literature.

00:07:57.940 --> 00:08:01.150
Here's one article from
"Science" stemming the alarming

00:08:01.150 --> 00:08:02.770
trends in the world's
fisheries demand

00:08:02.770 --> 00:08:04.840
a fundamental change in
management and fishing

00:08:04.840 --> 00:08:06.300
practices.

00:08:06.300 --> 00:08:10.980
Another paper points to the
lack of an integrated solution

00:08:10.980 --> 00:08:13.750
to the complexity in
managing world resources.

00:08:13.750 --> 00:08:17.100
And we have not achieved
that integrated solution.

00:08:17.100 --> 00:08:19.120
Of course, an
integrated solution

00:08:19.120 --> 00:08:23.950
must be based on
integrated data.

00:08:23.950 --> 00:08:26.250
There's really no
other way around that.

00:08:26.250 --> 00:08:30.220
And so, then, the next
step is model revolution.

00:08:30.220 --> 00:08:32.100
But there's a famous
fisheries biologist

00:08:32.100 --> 00:08:34.120
in the University of Washington.

00:08:34.120 --> 00:08:36.010
His name is Ray Hilborn.

00:08:36.010 --> 00:08:39.429
And he points to the fact
that managing fisheries

00:08:39.429 --> 00:08:41.250
is managing people, right?

00:08:41.250 --> 00:08:42.789
We don't manage fish.

00:08:42.789 --> 00:08:44.640
We manage fishermen.

00:08:44.640 --> 00:08:48.760
And here he says that, I believe
rocket scientists have it easy.

00:08:48.760 --> 00:08:50.700
The USA was able to
put a man on the moon

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:53.320
within a decade of
setting that goal.

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:55.790
Achieving biologically and
economically sustainable

00:08:55.790 --> 00:08:58.560
fisheries has
proven more elusive.

00:08:58.560 --> 00:09:04.550
He even alludes to the idea
of physics envy, right?

00:09:04.550 --> 00:09:07.560
So physicists and
pure mathematicians--

00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:10.910
they're able to have their
experiments with closed

00:09:10.910 --> 00:09:14.140
variables and actually
run them and get results.

00:09:14.140 --> 00:09:15.730
With ocean management
and fisheries,

00:09:15.730 --> 00:09:17.330
we don't have that luxury.

00:09:17.330 --> 00:09:20.740
We have to deal with not only
the vastness of the ocean

00:09:20.740 --> 00:09:22.930
but the complexity of
the human dimension

00:09:22.930 --> 00:09:25.860
because it's the
humans who are fishing

00:09:25.860 --> 00:09:27.920
and the humans who are
running the models giving

00:09:27.920 --> 00:09:30.160
the scientific advice.

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:33.230
So, in the Kuhn cycle, the
next step is model revolution.

00:09:33.230 --> 00:09:37.240
And this happens when you
figure out what you really need.

00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:41.760
In a fisheries perspective,
this is a systems view.

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:44.280
Now, there's three parts
of the fishery system.

00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:49.920
This is from a book in 2012
by Tony Charles in Canada.

00:09:49.920 --> 00:09:52.850
We're used to talking about
the natural ecosystem, about

00:09:52.850 --> 00:09:55.110
our fish and our fishing quotas.

00:09:55.110 --> 00:09:59.980
We're not used to talking about
how the natural ecosystem has

00:09:59.980 --> 00:10:02.180
feedbacks with the
management system.

00:10:02.180 --> 00:10:03.870
So when we set a
fishing quota and it's

00:10:03.870 --> 00:10:05.980
implemented and the
politics of sharing

00:10:05.980 --> 00:10:10.000
fishing quotas, the politics
of negotiating fishing quotas

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.440
and how that connects
to the human system.

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:15.600
So you have community,
consumers, households,

00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:18.960
people who are eating fish,
people who are processing fish,

00:10:18.960 --> 00:10:21.670
people who are fixing
boats that fishermen use.

00:10:21.670 --> 00:10:24.150
This is all integrated.

00:10:24.150 --> 00:10:27.060
And you can only
approach this when

00:10:27.060 --> 00:10:29.620
you're talking about
interdisciplinary science.

00:10:29.620 --> 00:10:33.190
Each of these three systems
has quantifiable data

00:10:33.190 --> 00:10:34.940
that we can get.

00:10:34.940 --> 00:10:37.190
And if you want to
look at fisheries

00:10:37.190 --> 00:10:39.550
and manage the
oceans sustainably,

00:10:39.550 --> 00:10:41.750
you must not forget
this complexity.

00:10:41.750 --> 00:10:44.670
We're not going to
solve the sustainability

00:10:44.670 --> 00:10:47.300
issues in our ocean
by only looking

00:10:47.300 --> 00:10:49.710
at the natural ecosystem.

00:10:49.710 --> 00:10:54.060
Which has been the status
quo the last 50 years.

00:10:54.060 --> 00:10:55.530
So that's our model revolution.

00:10:55.530 --> 00:10:57.330
You figure out what
you really need.

00:10:57.330 --> 00:10:58.720
We need a systems view.

00:10:58.720 --> 00:11:02.830
We need to incorporate the data
from different parts, not just

00:11:02.830 --> 00:11:04.670
the biological system.

00:11:04.670 --> 00:11:07.120
And then in the Kuhn
cycle in this book,

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:10.090
in 1962, "The Structure of
Scientific Revolutions,"

00:11:10.090 --> 00:11:14.020
he talks about paradigm
change is the next step.

00:11:14.020 --> 00:11:17.080
He's the one who coined
the term "paradigm shift."

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:18.620
You've probably heard of that.

00:11:18.620 --> 00:11:22.440
And in order to get a
paradigm change in science,

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:24.530
you have to get some
sort of consensus.

00:11:24.530 --> 00:11:26.470
And this is what
is kind of missing,

00:11:26.470 --> 00:11:30.590
and this is what I want to
put forward as a missing link.

00:11:30.590 --> 00:11:32.510
Let me just show
you this dichotomy

00:11:32.510 --> 00:11:36.230
between normal science
and post-normal science

00:11:36.230 --> 00:11:38.370
is the term I'm going
to introduce right now.

00:11:38.370 --> 00:11:41.220
Normal science is what
I've just been alluding to.

00:11:41.220 --> 00:11:44.310
This Thomas Kuhn's
definition-- puzzle-solving,

00:11:44.310 --> 00:11:46.320
relatively routine
work of scientists,

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:48.860
experimenting within
a paradigm and never

00:11:48.860 --> 00:11:50.480
really challenging
that paradigm.

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:52.640
They're just doing
their day-to-day work.

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:55.420
Whereas post-normal
science, by my colleagues

00:11:55.420 --> 00:11:59.000
Silvio Funtowicz and
Jerry Ravetz-- Silvio

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:00.780
is still a professor.

00:12:00.780 --> 00:12:02.570
He's been all over the
world, but now he's

00:12:02.570 --> 00:12:05.180
landed in Bergen, which
is exciting for us.

00:12:05.180 --> 00:12:07.310
And Jerry Ravetz,
who just retired.

00:12:07.310 --> 00:12:09.520
In the early '90s,
they put forward this.

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:11.350
Post-normal science
is a methodology

00:12:11.350 --> 00:12:16.650
of inquiry for cases
where facts are uncertain,

00:12:16.650 --> 00:12:19.410
values are in dispute,
stakes are high,

00:12:19.410 --> 00:12:21.790
and decisions are urgent.

00:12:21.790 --> 00:12:23.860
Now, the poster
child for post-normal

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:26.080
is climate science, right?

00:12:26.080 --> 00:12:28.990
You have very uncertain
models, uncertain predictions,

00:12:28.990 --> 00:12:31.590
at the same time,
values are in dispute.

00:12:31.590 --> 00:12:33.350
Who is going to pay?

00:12:33.350 --> 00:12:34.180
for example.

00:12:34.180 --> 00:12:37.090
The stakes are high, and
the decisions are urgent.

00:12:37.090 --> 00:12:39.390
We must make decisions
today if we're

00:12:39.390 --> 00:12:42.360
going to get on a
sustainable path.

00:12:42.360 --> 00:12:44.610
But since values are
embedded in science,

00:12:44.610 --> 00:12:47.050
post-normal science should
integrate stakeholders

00:12:47.050 --> 00:12:49.150
in an extended peer community.

00:12:49.150 --> 00:12:51.490
The extended peer
community means

00:12:51.490 --> 00:12:53.720
that sometimes the
questions scientists

00:12:53.720 --> 00:12:57.510
are asked when having
to advise policy

00:12:57.510 --> 00:12:59.590
are not scientific questions.

00:12:59.590 --> 00:13:01.430
They're questions
based on values,

00:13:01.430 --> 00:13:03.680
based on the
objectives for society.

00:13:03.680 --> 00:13:05.930
And this is the
post-normal paradigm.

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:08.120
This is where you have
to get different people

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:11.360
around the same table
to discuss this.

00:13:11.360 --> 00:13:15.340
So in this diagram, you have, on
the x-axis, systems uncertainty

00:13:15.340 --> 00:13:18.980
from low to high and
decision stakes on the y-axis

00:13:18.980 --> 00:13:20.220
from low to high.

00:13:20.220 --> 00:13:22.730
And that green area in the
bottom left-hand corner

00:13:22.730 --> 00:13:24.900
is where you have
applied science.

00:13:24.900 --> 00:13:28.000
This is the physics envy,
where you have low systems

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.670
uncertainty but the decision
stakes are very big.

00:13:31.670 --> 00:13:34.060
Professional consultancy
is the next level,

00:13:34.060 --> 00:13:37.570
and post-normal science is this
area where systems uncertainty

00:13:37.570 --> 00:13:41.280
is high as well as
the decision stakes.

00:13:41.280 --> 00:13:41.780
OK.

00:13:41.780 --> 00:13:44.800
So now I've introduced the
idea of post-normal science

00:13:44.800 --> 00:13:47.260
and maybe you think,
OK, that could be right.

00:13:47.260 --> 00:13:48.760
But what does it
actually look like?

00:13:48.760 --> 00:13:50.830
Can you put it into pictures?

00:13:50.830 --> 00:13:56.130
Normal science a la
Kuhn is this poor woman

00:13:56.130 --> 00:13:57.980
under all her papers,
this academic.

00:13:57.980 --> 00:14:01.790
It's mono-disciplinary,
technocratic, certain,

00:14:01.790 --> 00:14:02.900
and predictive.

00:14:02.900 --> 00:14:06.380
Whereas post-normal science
is academic and social,

00:14:06.380 --> 00:14:09.760
trans-disciplinary,
participative, uncertain,

00:14:09.760 --> 00:14:11.480
and exploratory.

00:14:11.480 --> 00:14:14.770
And you have people around
the table, different experts

00:14:14.770 --> 00:14:18.050
from different disciplines,
also including the stakeholders

00:14:18.050 --> 00:14:19.940
and politicians.

00:14:19.940 --> 00:14:23.630
So perhaps one of the reasons
that we've had so much trouble

00:14:23.630 --> 00:14:27.170
managing our natural renewable
resources and climate change,

00:14:27.170 --> 00:14:30.740
for example, is that it's hard
for us to admit that science

00:14:30.740 --> 00:14:32.920
cannot give us the one answer.

00:14:32.920 --> 00:14:36.310
Even if we had all the
best data in the world,

00:14:36.310 --> 00:14:40.930
we still have values and other
social concerns at stake.

00:14:40.930 --> 00:14:44.460
Which are not necessarily
scientific questions.

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:45.050
OK.

00:14:45.050 --> 00:14:48.090
So I gave you a little
bit of background.

00:14:48.090 --> 00:14:53.980
And I'm going to now focus
more specifically on oceans.

00:14:53.980 --> 00:14:57.640
And here are some illustrations
by my friend and colleague

00:14:57.640 --> 00:15:01.700
Mariano [INAUDIBLE], who's
at the University of Valencia

00:15:01.700 --> 00:15:06.300
in Spain, to kind of illustrate
the problems that we have

00:15:06.300 --> 00:15:09.180
from an ocean and
fisheries perspective.

00:15:09.180 --> 00:15:12.350
So this is a music box.

00:15:12.350 --> 00:15:16.540
And one thing that we learn from
studying ecosystems and giving

00:15:16.540 --> 00:15:19.680
ecosystem-based
advice is the whole

00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:21.880
is greater than the
sum of the parts.

00:15:21.880 --> 00:15:25.730
And I put the whole
as a capital W.

00:15:25.730 --> 00:15:28.910
And when I talk about the
Ocean, I use a capital O.

00:15:28.910 --> 00:15:32.500
And this is because
this is one word that's

00:15:32.500 --> 00:15:35.460
encompassing very many things.

00:15:35.460 --> 00:15:38.510
And a music box, you can
break it down to its parts.

00:15:38.510 --> 00:15:40.560
But you can never
necessarily guess

00:15:40.560 --> 00:15:43.810
from its parts, when you
turn the crank and the music

00:15:43.810 --> 00:15:47.470
comes out, how that affects
you as a person, what joys,

00:15:47.470 --> 00:15:49.620
or what turmoils, or
everything that you

00:15:49.620 --> 00:15:54.030
get from that music, kind of
illustrating that the whole is

00:15:54.030 --> 00:15:56.230
greater than the
sum of the parts.

00:15:56.230 --> 00:15:58.310
Now, here's our history lesson.

00:15:58.310 --> 00:16:00.840
We're going to go all the way
back to the French Revolution.

00:16:00.840 --> 00:16:04.020
And this train of thought
is coming from the professor

00:16:04.020 --> 00:16:06.301
emeritus at Harvard EO Wilson.

00:16:06.301 --> 00:16:07.800
I don't know if
you've heard of him.

00:16:07.800 --> 00:16:08.630
He's still living.

00:16:08.630 --> 00:16:10.060
He's approaching 90.

00:16:10.060 --> 00:16:13.680
He has a book from 1998
called "Consilience

00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:15.250
the Unity of Knowledge."

00:16:15.250 --> 00:16:17.920
And he explains in the
introduction of the book

00:16:17.920 --> 00:16:21.270
that we can really blame a
lot of our scientific problems

00:16:21.270 --> 00:16:22.630
on the French Revolution.

00:16:22.630 --> 00:16:25.600
And let me quickly
explained that.

00:16:25.600 --> 00:16:28.480
Before the French Revolution,
you had a monarchy, right?

00:16:28.480 --> 00:16:30.450
All the different
scientists in the kingdom

00:16:30.450 --> 00:16:34.000
were reporting to
one person, the king.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.250
So if the king had a grand
challenge or a problem

00:16:37.250 --> 00:16:40.960
or something that he
wanted to fix or find out.

00:16:40.960 --> 00:16:43.170
For example, I want
to have the best

00:16:43.170 --> 00:16:46.110
wine in all of the kingdoms.

00:16:46.110 --> 00:16:49.960
So he would put his
biologists, his scientists,

00:16:49.960 --> 00:16:52.620
his philosophers,
his economists all at

00:16:52.620 --> 00:16:54.920
work for that one
single purpose.

00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:58.285
And so the biologists would have
to make the perfect vineyards.

00:16:58.285 --> 00:16:59.910
The economists would
have to figure out

00:16:59.910 --> 00:17:02.990
how to do it efficiently
to scale it up.

00:17:02.990 --> 00:17:05.740
The philosophers would have
to think, what makes the best

00:17:05.740 --> 00:17:07.939
wine? and all those
types of things.

00:17:07.939 --> 00:17:10.480
But at the end of the day, they
were reporting to one person.

00:17:10.480 --> 00:17:13.480
So it was a unity of knowledge.

00:17:13.480 --> 00:17:16.940
After the French Revolution,
they cut the king's head off,

00:17:16.940 --> 00:17:18.970
cut Marie Antoinette's head off.

00:17:18.970 --> 00:17:23.829
And now the political
system is more democratic.

00:17:23.829 --> 00:17:24.680
It's more flat.

00:17:24.680 --> 00:17:28.550
It's not this top-down,
hierarchical system.

00:17:28.550 --> 00:17:32.550
And the disciplines in science
became very disciplined,

00:17:32.550 --> 00:17:36.390
which was great because we
had a huge advances in math,

00:17:36.390 --> 00:17:40.370
and biology, genetics, all
these different things.

00:17:40.370 --> 00:17:45.520
But in the 21st century,
we're still thinking, OK,

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:49.670
that's great that we know
how to sequence DNA and do

00:17:49.670 --> 00:17:50.350
all this stuff.

00:17:50.350 --> 00:17:51.460
Great.

00:17:51.460 --> 00:17:53.330
Where's the cure for cancer?

00:17:53.330 --> 00:17:55.020
How are we going to get there?

00:17:55.020 --> 00:17:58.110
Because what we know
is the grand challenges

00:17:58.110 --> 00:18:00.650
that we have today in
society-- climate change

00:18:00.650 --> 00:18:03.590
and all of these things--
is not up to one discipline.

00:18:03.590 --> 00:18:06.180
You must have a
unity of knowledge.

00:18:06.180 --> 00:18:08.310
So after the French
Revolution, the disciplines

00:18:08.310 --> 00:18:10.780
separated from the whole.

00:18:10.780 --> 00:18:13.716
And we got a very
disciplined view of science.

00:18:13.716 --> 00:18:15.340
Here's a picture of
a fisherman looking

00:18:15.340 --> 00:18:18.490
through a little peephole
as an illustration

00:18:18.490 --> 00:18:20.600
that the ocean is very vast.

00:18:20.600 --> 00:18:23.650
If we just use biology
in our limited views

00:18:23.650 --> 00:18:25.800
of how we can look
at the ocean, we're

00:18:25.800 --> 00:18:27.850
not getting the whole system.

00:18:27.850 --> 00:18:29.980
We're too disciplined.

00:18:29.980 --> 00:18:32.750
And this leads us to very
confused and frustrated

00:18:32.750 --> 00:18:33.910
decision-makers.

00:18:33.910 --> 00:18:35.790
Here you have a
decision-maker who

00:18:35.790 --> 00:18:37.540
has three different
scientists telling him

00:18:37.540 --> 00:18:38.590
three different things.

00:18:38.590 --> 00:18:39.980
Three different sources of data.

00:18:39.980 --> 00:18:41.170
What's going on?

00:18:41.170 --> 00:18:43.050
The decision-maker
then makes a decision

00:18:43.050 --> 00:18:47.380
based on the stakeholder or the
scientist who yells the loudest

00:18:47.380 --> 00:18:49.420
or whom he trusts the most.

00:18:49.420 --> 00:18:54.560
And we get politics
not necessarily based

00:18:54.560 --> 00:18:57.780
on a collective view of science.

00:18:57.780 --> 00:19:00.270
So there's a call for
consilience of knowledge, which

00:19:00.270 --> 00:19:03.280
means unity of knowledge,
moving towards interdisciplinary

00:19:03.280 --> 00:19:04.720
and systems view of the whole.

00:19:04.720 --> 00:19:06.970
This is the picture
post-normal science.

00:19:06.970 --> 00:19:10.220
This is where you have your
biologists, your politician,

00:19:10.220 --> 00:19:13.950
your philosopher, your
fisherman, your economists all

00:19:13.950 --> 00:19:14.900
around the same table.

00:19:14.900 --> 00:19:17.080
It's a very iterative process.

00:19:17.080 --> 00:19:18.830
Many, many meetings.

00:19:18.830 --> 00:19:22.070
The thing is that the
system has to be driven,

00:19:22.070 --> 00:19:26.710
that everybody is in
on this game of getting

00:19:26.710 --> 00:19:28.840
together and talking
and talking and talking

00:19:28.840 --> 00:19:33.270
and talking and discussing
how we put these together,

00:19:33.270 --> 00:19:38.000
what data is useful for
us, and all these things.

00:19:40.311 --> 00:19:40.810
OK.

00:19:40.810 --> 00:19:43.020
Let's get a little
bit towards solutions.

00:19:43.020 --> 00:19:46.799
I think it's important
to have this idea that,

00:19:46.799 --> 00:19:48.340
OK, if there's a
will, there's a way.

00:19:48.340 --> 00:19:50.500
We have tons of data.

00:19:50.500 --> 00:19:52.810
If there's one thing that we
do well it's collect data.

00:19:52.810 --> 00:19:55.850
I'm going to show you some
examples of the type of data

00:19:55.850 --> 00:19:59.690
that we collect in fisheries
and ocean management.

00:19:59.690 --> 00:20:02.220
But it's very
important that we have

00:20:02.220 --> 00:20:04.480
this idea of the
focus imaginarius.

00:20:04.480 --> 00:20:09.520
The 18th century
philosopher Immanuel Kant

00:20:09.520 --> 00:20:12.240
describes the focus
imaginarius as such.

00:20:12.240 --> 00:20:15.570
It is something that you know
very well what it looks like.

00:20:15.570 --> 00:20:16.980
It's the perfect picture.

00:20:16.980 --> 00:20:19.080
It's the perfect ocean
managed perfectly.

00:20:19.080 --> 00:20:20.700
Everybody's perfectly happy.

00:20:20.700 --> 00:20:25.050
It's what you can imagine could
happen, and it's your focus.

00:20:25.050 --> 00:20:28.090
You're not naive to think that
you're ever going to get there,

00:20:28.090 --> 00:20:31.460
but you must have some
sort of goal to go towards.

00:20:31.460 --> 00:20:35.520
So I'm going to show you
three steps on will and way.

00:20:35.520 --> 00:20:37.960
So as will gets higher
and way gets higher,

00:20:37.960 --> 00:20:42.220
you get closer to your
focus imaginarius.

00:20:42.220 --> 00:20:45.220
So first let's talk
about status quo.

00:20:45.220 --> 00:20:48.170
What do we do today when we
are giving fishing advice

00:20:48.170 --> 00:20:50.790
and managing the ocean?

00:20:50.790 --> 00:20:53.320
This is taken from ICES.

00:20:53.320 --> 00:20:56.340
So it's I-C-E-S. It stands
for the International Council

00:20:56.340 --> 00:20:58.500
for the Exploration of the Sea.

00:20:58.500 --> 00:21:02.100
ICES is the world's oldest
intergovernmental organization.

00:21:02.100 --> 00:21:06.520
It's over 100 years old
and collects all the data

00:21:06.520 --> 00:21:08.630
in Europe, with
some collaboration

00:21:08.630 --> 00:21:11.880
with Canada and
the United States.

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:13.730
Does the science, does
the stock assessments

00:21:13.730 --> 00:21:15.780
to give the fishing advice.

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:18.850
Now, there is no real
will, political will

00:21:18.850 --> 00:21:20.200
for an integrated assessment.

00:21:20.200 --> 00:21:23.610
The politicians don't know how
they would use it, basically.

00:21:23.610 --> 00:21:27.410
So ICES keeps doing status
quo, single stock assessment

00:21:27.410 --> 00:21:29.030
and derives their advice.

00:21:29.030 --> 00:21:33.380
This is the popularized
sheet that they give out

00:21:33.380 --> 00:21:34.580
for each stock.

00:21:34.580 --> 00:21:37.480
There's a lot more sheets.

00:21:37.480 --> 00:21:39.980
The whole assessment
working group report

00:21:39.980 --> 00:21:42.620
could be from 100
to 200 pages long,

00:21:42.620 --> 00:21:45.150
but they give this sheet
as a popularized version.

00:21:45.150 --> 00:21:47.536
This is for cod
in the North Sea.

00:21:47.536 --> 00:21:53.190
For 2014, the advice was that,
based on the EU Norway Plan,

00:21:53.190 --> 00:21:59.160
the landings in 2014 should be
no more than 28,809 tons, which

00:21:59.160 --> 00:22:03.730
happens to be 9% less than the
2013 total allowable catch.

00:22:03.730 --> 00:22:04.230
OK.

00:22:04.230 --> 00:22:05.280
What does this mean?

00:22:05.280 --> 00:22:08.510
28,809 tons.

00:22:08.510 --> 00:22:10.670
Here we have five
significant digits.

00:22:10.670 --> 00:22:16.190
So you might think that the
science of stock assessment

00:22:16.190 --> 00:22:17.790
is really quite certain.

00:22:17.790 --> 00:22:18.290
OK.

00:22:18.290 --> 00:22:20.373
Well, they really know
what they're talking about.

00:22:20.373 --> 00:22:22.410
For one year, they can
fish that much and this

00:22:22.410 --> 00:22:26.480
is going to result in
sustainable fishing.

00:22:26.480 --> 00:22:30.670
The fact of the matter is this
is very, very sloppy work on

00:22:30.670 --> 00:22:31.630
how we give advice.

00:22:31.630 --> 00:22:34.510
There's no way we
could ever have

00:22:34.510 --> 00:22:37.930
five significant
digits of certainty.

00:22:37.930 --> 00:22:40.880
I call it sloppy, but
this is just routine.

00:22:40.880 --> 00:22:43.420
This is how they've been
doing it for 20 years.

00:22:43.420 --> 00:22:45.350
This is what the
policy makers expect.

00:22:45.350 --> 00:22:46.670
This has been negotiated.

00:22:46.670 --> 00:22:49.330
This is what is done.

00:22:49.330 --> 00:22:52.440
That's a basis of
a whole other talk

00:22:52.440 --> 00:22:54.390
that I just gave at [INAUDIBLE].

00:22:54.390 --> 00:22:57.470
So I'm starting to do
something about this.

00:22:57.470 --> 00:23:01.920
But first we have to be serious
about what science can give us

00:23:01.920 --> 00:23:03.500
and what science can't give us.

00:23:03.500 --> 00:23:05.110
Science can't give
us that certainty.

00:23:05.110 --> 00:23:07.910
And we have to be honest
with our policy makers

00:23:07.910 --> 00:23:09.710
on what science
can do and not do.

00:23:09.710 --> 00:23:12.460
It's part of the
Occupy Science Movement

00:23:12.460 --> 00:23:15.290
that I allude to a
little bit later.

00:23:15.290 --> 00:23:15.790
OK.

00:23:15.790 --> 00:23:18.520
So getting a little
bit more will

00:23:18.520 --> 00:23:21.540
to do an integrated assessment
and a little bit combining

00:23:21.540 --> 00:23:22.810
more data sources.

00:23:22.810 --> 00:23:25.350
I have this paper from 2009.

00:23:25.350 --> 00:23:27.270
You might actually
recognize this map.

00:23:27.270 --> 00:23:30.870
So here we are in Cambridge.

00:23:30.870 --> 00:23:33.600
And here off the coast of
Massachusetts and Cape Cod

00:23:33.600 --> 00:23:34.660
is Georges Bank.

00:23:34.660 --> 00:23:37.110
Maybe you have heard
of Georges Bank.

00:23:37.110 --> 00:23:39.060
Used to be one of the
most productive fishing

00:23:39.060 --> 00:23:40.560
areas in the world.

00:23:40.560 --> 00:23:43.600
People have been fishing
there for over 1,000 years.

00:23:43.600 --> 00:23:46.620
In Georges Bank, you have a
really interesting dynamic

00:23:46.620 --> 00:23:49.410
at the current moment right now.

00:23:49.410 --> 00:23:53.320
I have overlaid this map on
some of the data from NOAA.

00:23:53.320 --> 00:23:55.880
I'm just going to explain
the axes really quickly.

00:23:55.880 --> 00:23:59.550
The x-axis here is your biomass.

00:23:59.550 --> 00:24:01.800
This is the data
from 2007, and this

00:24:01.800 --> 00:24:04.710
is over the biomass at
maximum sustainable yield.

00:24:04.710 --> 00:24:07.680
MSY is our term there.

00:24:07.680 --> 00:24:11.790
So basically from zero to a lot.

00:24:11.790 --> 00:24:15.240
And on the y-axis, our
fishing mortality rate.

00:24:15.240 --> 00:24:18.690
This is how much fishing is
happening in proportion, where

00:24:18.690 --> 00:24:21.340
you have zero fishing
here and a lot.

00:24:21.340 --> 00:24:24.100
So in this area where
it's red, the fish

00:24:24.100 --> 00:24:27.000
that are plotted-- each
of these little dots

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:30.980
is a fish stock from
Georges Bank-- in this area,

00:24:30.980 --> 00:24:33.330
the fish plotted
here are overfished

00:24:33.330 --> 00:24:35.540
and overfishing is occurring.

00:24:35.540 --> 00:24:37.910
Whereas down here where
you have a lot of biomass

00:24:37.910 --> 00:24:40.380
and not a lot of
fishing happening,

00:24:40.380 --> 00:24:43.060
these stocks are not
overfishing and overfishing

00:24:43.060 --> 00:24:44.810
is not occurring.

00:24:44.810 --> 00:24:46.590
So what you have here
on Georges Bank--

00:24:46.590 --> 00:24:48.465
you have Georges
Bank haddock here.

00:24:48.465 --> 00:24:49.590
This is what it looks like.

00:24:49.590 --> 00:24:51.810
You have a lot, a surplus.

00:24:51.810 --> 00:24:54.600
We still have a surplus on
Georges Bank of haddock,

00:24:54.600 --> 00:24:57.640
but Georges Bank
cod and yellow tail

00:24:57.640 --> 00:25:01.590
flounder are overfished and
overfishing is occurring.

00:25:01.590 --> 00:25:05.580
Which means the fishermen want
to target haddock and leave

00:25:05.580 --> 00:25:07.870
the cod and yellowtail to be.

00:25:07.870 --> 00:25:11.100
However, they cannot do
this because the technology,

00:25:11.100 --> 00:25:15.700
the gear technology, when
they're dragging the Otter

00:25:15.700 --> 00:25:18.520
trawl, the net, along the sea
bottom and destroying a lot

00:25:18.520 --> 00:25:21.940
of habitat in their wake,
they're catching cod and yellow

00:25:21.940 --> 00:25:24.330
tail as a by-catch of haddock.

00:25:24.330 --> 00:25:31.420
They cannot only target haddock
until relatively recently.

00:25:31.420 --> 00:25:32.420
And let me just explain.

00:25:32.420 --> 00:25:36.697
This is why I wanted to have
a mic that moves because this

00:25:36.697 --> 00:25:38.530
is where I get to use
my hands a little bit.

00:25:41.900 --> 00:25:43.140
This is where biology comes.

00:25:43.140 --> 00:25:47.720
When the trawl-- this is
the trawl, the net-- when

00:25:47.720 --> 00:25:49.670
it's being dragged
along the sea floor,

00:25:49.670 --> 00:25:52.450
the reaction, the biological
reaction, for haddock

00:25:52.450 --> 00:25:53.826
is to swim up.

00:25:53.826 --> 00:25:55.200
It doesn't want
to go in the net.

00:25:55.200 --> 00:25:56.700
They're not that dumb.

00:25:56.700 --> 00:25:57.870
And it swims up.

00:25:57.870 --> 00:26:02.260
Whereas the cod and the yellow
tail swim down along the floor.

00:26:02.260 --> 00:26:04.660
These are all bottom creatures.

00:26:04.660 --> 00:26:07.650
So some fishermen and some
scientists got this good idea

00:26:07.650 --> 00:26:09.890
and they created the Ruhle
trawl, which is basically

00:26:09.890 --> 00:26:11.640
the same thing as
an Otter trawl,

00:26:11.640 --> 00:26:14.900
but they just lift it one
yard off the bottom of the sea

00:26:14.900 --> 00:26:15.814
floor.

00:26:15.814 --> 00:26:17.730
That way, as the net is
coming-- and then it's

00:26:17.730 --> 00:26:20.730
not being dragged
along the sea floor

00:26:20.730 --> 00:26:22.890
as they usually are-- the
cod and the yellow tail

00:26:22.890 --> 00:26:26.570
will dive down and haddock
will dive up and be caught.

00:26:26.570 --> 00:26:28.100
So you can catch them.

00:26:28.100 --> 00:26:29.760
And this is really
interesting where

00:26:29.760 --> 00:26:33.580
you can use gear technology
from an ecological perspective

00:26:33.580 --> 00:26:35.510
and from an economic
perspective.

00:26:35.510 --> 00:26:37.940
We want to target the haddock.

00:26:37.940 --> 00:26:39.490
There's also this
separator trawl

00:26:39.490 --> 00:26:41.640
which does essentially
the same thing.

00:26:41.640 --> 00:26:44.620
The cod and the yellow
tail flounder go down here

00:26:44.620 --> 00:26:46.714
and they go outside the net.

00:26:46.714 --> 00:26:48.380
Whereas the haddock,
they go up and they

00:26:48.380 --> 00:26:51.540
get into what we call the cod
end, the part of the net where

00:26:51.540 --> 00:26:53.160
they're caught.

00:26:53.160 --> 00:26:56.720
So I wanted to do an
analysis for the fishermen

00:26:56.720 --> 00:26:59.130
because they were
skeptical about changing

00:26:59.130 --> 00:27:00.380
their gear to the Rhule trawl.

00:27:00.380 --> 00:27:01.820
They didn't know how
it was going to work.

00:27:01.820 --> 00:27:03.194
They didn't know
if they're going

00:27:03.194 --> 00:27:04.890
to get their yields
and their money.

00:27:04.890 --> 00:27:08.340
So we put together the
biological data and the stock

00:27:08.340 --> 00:27:11.710
assessments we had
for all nine stocks

00:27:11.710 --> 00:27:14.520
that we have data
for in Georges Bank.

00:27:14.520 --> 00:27:21.270
And we have the profitability
surveys and the economic data

00:27:21.270 --> 00:27:25.180
from some of the
economists at NOAA.

00:27:25.180 --> 00:27:27.730
And we can show these
trade-offs, right?

00:27:27.730 --> 00:27:30.050
Because unless we have
the biological data

00:27:30.050 --> 00:27:34.620
and the employment data and
the economic data together,

00:27:34.620 --> 00:27:41.540
we can't coherently show
trade-offs to the policymakers.

00:27:41.540 --> 00:27:43.891
So here are the
three different lines

00:27:43.891 --> 00:27:45.140
of the three different trawls.

00:27:45.140 --> 00:27:47.700
I won't go into so many details
but the point of the matter

00:27:47.700 --> 00:27:51.430
is here, where you're getting
lots of yield and lots

00:27:51.430 --> 00:27:54.740
of producer surplus, which
is a proxy for profit,

00:27:54.740 --> 00:27:58.090
you have the trade-off of
the different other stocks.

00:27:58.090 --> 00:28:01.830
These are the mixed species of
the by-catch stocks going down.

00:28:01.830 --> 00:28:06.457
And so we can look at different
amount of days at sea.

00:28:06.457 --> 00:28:08.040
For example, we can
look at status quo

00:28:08.040 --> 00:28:11.260
and see the results
on the economic,

00:28:11.260 --> 00:28:14.270
the results on employment, and
the results to the ecosystem.

00:28:14.270 --> 00:28:17.800
This is just an example
of what could be done.

00:28:17.800 --> 00:28:21.340
I took this paper to the
Massachusetts State House

00:28:21.340 --> 00:28:24.066
in 2009 to State
Senator Bruce Tarr

00:28:24.066 --> 00:28:26.440
who said, oh, it's great that
you scientists are actually

00:28:26.440 --> 00:28:29.440
using those socioeconomic
assessments that NOAA always

00:28:29.440 --> 00:28:32.840
does but it's never combined
with the biological ones.

00:28:32.840 --> 00:28:37.330
So there's a little
bit of work there,

00:28:37.330 --> 00:28:39.190
but we can go a
little bit further.

00:28:39.190 --> 00:28:43.650
This is some work that I'm
in the process of where we're

00:28:43.650 --> 00:28:45.910
trying to look at
stakeholder conflicts

00:28:45.910 --> 00:28:50.670
because a large
amount of stakeholders

00:28:50.670 --> 00:28:53.120
are interested in fisheries.

00:28:53.120 --> 00:28:55.360
And how do we find the
management strategy

00:28:55.360 --> 00:28:58.470
that is going to satisfy the
most amount of stakeholders?

00:28:58.470 --> 00:29:00.880
That's a very, very
interesting question.

00:29:00.880 --> 00:29:04.570
Very little work is done that
usually quantifies utility

00:29:04.570 --> 00:29:07.520
functions for stakeholders
for [INAUDIBLE] so this

00:29:07.520 --> 00:29:10.730
is some work that
we've pioneered.

00:29:10.730 --> 00:29:13.260
These are examples
of stakeholders.

00:29:13.260 --> 00:29:16.120
Up here, you have your
industrial fisherman.

00:29:16.120 --> 00:29:18.890
You have two different
representatives of society.

00:29:18.890 --> 00:29:20.520
This is from a
Norwegian context where

00:29:20.520 --> 00:29:22.520
we have the Norwegian
fisheries minister who

00:29:22.520 --> 00:29:24.430
was from the right
party, who wanted

00:29:24.430 --> 00:29:27.810
profitable fisheries,
big boats, kind

00:29:27.810 --> 00:29:32.250
of this profit-centered
rhetoric.

00:29:32.250 --> 00:29:35.230
And after him was the
first female fisheries

00:29:35.230 --> 00:29:36.240
minister in Norway.

00:29:36.240 --> 00:29:40.060
She was representing
a lot of minorities

00:29:40.060 --> 00:29:42.715
at the same time when she was
appointed fisheries minister

00:29:42.715 --> 00:29:43.590
from the Labor Party.

00:29:43.590 --> 00:29:46.170
She was not only the
first woman there.

00:29:46.170 --> 00:29:48.850
She was of Sami dissent,
from the Lapland country

00:29:48.850 --> 00:29:52.212
in the north of Norway
and she was pregnant.

00:29:52.212 --> 00:29:52.920
So that was cool.

00:29:52.920 --> 00:29:56.280
And her political philosophy
was that all of Norway,

00:29:56.280 --> 00:29:58.750
which has one of the largest
coastlines in the world,

00:29:58.750 --> 00:30:00.780
should be lit up with
fishing villages.

00:30:00.780 --> 00:30:04.660
We want to put an emphasis
on employing people,

00:30:04.660 --> 00:30:07.440
the cultural value of
fisheries and whatnot.

00:30:07.440 --> 00:30:09.250
And then you have
environmentalists

00:30:09.250 --> 00:30:13.230
like Maren Esmark
at WWF in Oslo who

00:30:13.230 --> 00:30:16.540
has different utility
coming out of the fishery.

00:30:16.540 --> 00:30:18.940
And then you have your
small-scale coastal fisherman,

00:30:18.940 --> 00:30:20.880
your artisanal fisherman.

00:30:20.880 --> 00:30:23.400
And what's coming
out of the fishery

00:30:23.400 --> 00:30:25.750
are what we call utility
components like yield,

00:30:25.750 --> 00:30:29.300
profit, employment at
sea, employment at shore,

00:30:29.300 --> 00:30:33.890
and ecosystem preservation
also has value coming out

00:30:33.890 --> 00:30:35.160
of the fishery.

00:30:35.160 --> 00:30:39.360
And, basically, you can
make a utility function

00:30:39.360 --> 00:30:42.030
on how strong are
the preferences

00:30:42.030 --> 00:30:44.780
for each stakeholder on
these different components

00:30:44.780 --> 00:30:46.370
that we can get out.

00:30:46.370 --> 00:30:48.430
And then you would
quantify what we

00:30:48.430 --> 00:30:51.720
call the area of
joint satisfaction.

00:30:51.720 --> 00:30:56.890
So let's say this
is a generic showing

00:30:56.890 --> 00:30:59.400
the results for stakeholder
A for different management

00:30:59.400 --> 00:31:00.040
strategies.

00:31:00.040 --> 00:31:02.750
And in this blue zone, they
would be getting, for example,

00:31:02.750 --> 00:31:06.340
90% of their maximum utility.

00:31:06.340 --> 00:31:08.367
So they're pretty
happy in that area.

00:31:08.367 --> 00:31:10.200
Stakeholder B would be
getting, for example,

00:31:10.200 --> 00:31:14.410
90% in this area and then
just simply overlap them

00:31:14.410 --> 00:31:18.820
and talk about an area of where
you can start the negotiations.

00:31:18.820 --> 00:31:23.480
So you are already starting
with some sort of a consensus.

00:31:23.480 --> 00:31:25.860
This is avoiding where
you're starting from scratch

00:31:25.860 --> 00:31:29.720
and people are just going
to butt heads and not agree.

00:31:29.720 --> 00:31:31.990
So this is what
we've quantified.

00:31:31.990 --> 00:31:34.840
We call it the assessment of
joint stakeholder satisfaction,

00:31:34.840 --> 00:31:39.830
where we combine the data from
the different data sources,

00:31:39.830 --> 00:31:43.440
from the biology and from the
employment and economic model.

00:31:43.440 --> 00:31:45.810
And then we integrate
utility components,

00:31:45.810 --> 00:31:48.130
get stakeholder
specific total utility,

00:31:48.130 --> 00:31:50.790
and then get what we call the
JSS, the Joint Stakeholder

00:31:50.790 --> 00:31:51.830
Satisfaction.

00:31:51.830 --> 00:31:54.290
This is not routinely done.

00:31:54.290 --> 00:31:56.490
This is important to realize
because we don't even

00:31:56.490 --> 00:31:59.810
do integrated assessments
on this scale.

00:31:59.810 --> 00:32:01.845
There's scientists
around the world that

00:32:01.845 --> 00:32:04.100
are getting their fingers
wet and starting to do it,

00:32:04.100 --> 00:32:10.900
but we definitely don't do it on
a large political scale, which

00:32:10.900 --> 00:32:12.220
is needed.

00:32:12.220 --> 00:32:15.870
This is the one result I'm
going to show you from this.

00:32:15.870 --> 00:32:18.580
We did this-- quantified it
for Barents Sea Capelin, which

00:32:18.580 --> 00:32:21.940
is a small pelagic
fish that's sold

00:32:21.940 --> 00:32:24.530
on the Japanese market
for human consumption.

00:32:24.530 --> 00:32:27.237
This is a schooling fish
and we did it for cod,

00:32:27.237 --> 00:32:29.820
North Atlantic cod, which is a
much bigger, longer-lived fish,

00:32:29.820 --> 00:32:32.700
to see if there
were differences.

00:32:32.700 --> 00:32:34.550
I'm going to break
it down because this

00:32:34.550 --> 00:32:36.590
is a pretty heavy figure.

00:32:36.590 --> 00:32:39.730
On the x-axis, we have
harvest proportion,

00:32:39.730 --> 00:32:43.540
from zero to almost
100 percent fishing.

00:32:43.540 --> 00:32:47.160
And now we're doing this in
a computer simulation model,

00:32:47.160 --> 00:32:52.760
so we can actually do all
parameter space and look at it.

00:32:52.760 --> 00:32:56.090
And on the y-axis, you have
the minimum size of capture.

00:32:56.090 --> 00:32:58.650
So you guys are probably
familiar that-- if you're

00:32:58.650 --> 00:33:01.340
recreational fishing
and your fish is smaller

00:33:01.340 --> 00:33:03.950
than the minimum size,
you have to throw it back.

00:33:03.950 --> 00:33:08.084
So now we're simulating minimum
size of the whole spectrum

00:33:08.084 --> 00:33:09.500
for capelin, which
only gets to be

00:33:09.500 --> 00:33:11.890
about 18 centimeters
and cod, which

00:33:11.890 --> 00:33:14.640
gets to be about this big.

00:33:14.640 --> 00:33:17.520
For each data point,
each combination

00:33:17.520 --> 00:33:19.150
of harvest proportion--
for example,

00:33:19.150 --> 00:33:22.990
say you have 20% harvest
proportion and two centimeters

00:33:22.990 --> 00:33:25.415
minimum size-- that
represents a strategy.

00:33:25.415 --> 00:33:27.790
So you would fish this amount,
and you wouldn't fish them

00:33:27.790 --> 00:33:29.020
until they're this big.

00:33:33.500 --> 00:33:35.960
For each of these
management strategies,

00:33:35.960 --> 00:33:40.110
all five stakeholders
have their utility value.

00:33:40.110 --> 00:33:42.140
How much utility from
their utility function

00:33:42.140 --> 00:33:44.690
are they getting
with that strategy?

00:33:44.690 --> 00:33:47.690
And now we are getting into
a little bit of philosophy.

00:33:47.690 --> 00:33:50.510
We're not going to plot all
five of those stakeholders

00:33:50.510 --> 00:33:54.310
because, if we follow the
maxi-min principle by John

00:33:54.310 --> 00:33:57.220
Rawls who was a famous 20th
century philosopher-- he said

00:33:57.220 --> 00:34:01.400
the measure of a society
is how they take care

00:34:01.400 --> 00:34:04.520
of the least-advantaged
citizen, right?

00:34:04.520 --> 00:34:07.340
Which is a really
nice philosophy.

00:34:07.340 --> 00:34:09.580
I think a lot of people
can agree on that.

00:34:09.580 --> 00:34:11.909
So in that case,
we have the results

00:34:11.909 --> 00:34:13.020
of the five stakeholders.

00:34:13.020 --> 00:34:16.912
We only plot the stakeholder
who does the worst.

00:34:16.912 --> 00:34:18.370
We assume that we
want to take care

00:34:18.370 --> 00:34:20.370
of that stakeholder
looking for the consensus.

00:34:22.885 --> 00:34:24.260
We're concerned
when everybody is

00:34:24.260 --> 00:34:27.060
happy, not just two or
three people or one person.

00:34:27.060 --> 00:34:31.590
So this star represents where
all the stakeholders receive

00:34:31.590 --> 00:34:39.010
their maximum utility based on
the weakest link, basically.

00:34:39.010 --> 00:34:43.590
Which shows that we're fishing
a lot but at very large sizes

00:34:43.590 --> 00:34:47.170
because these circles
represent the status quo.

00:34:47.170 --> 00:34:49.389
Where we manage
fisheries today for cod.

00:34:49.389 --> 00:34:53.310
We manage them around
38% harvest proportion,

00:34:53.310 --> 00:34:56.550
and the minimum size
is 45 centimeters.

00:34:56.550 --> 00:34:58.200
This is really interesting.

00:34:58.200 --> 00:35:00.240
It's hard to know
how much trust--

00:35:00.240 --> 00:35:02.930
I've done a lot of
uncertainty analyses on this.

00:35:02.930 --> 00:35:04.440
And we're still doing this.

00:35:04.440 --> 00:35:07.720
The fact of the matter is we
get very different results.

00:35:07.720 --> 00:35:10.050
The status quo
management is based

00:35:10.050 --> 00:35:12.590
on the biological assessment.

00:35:12.590 --> 00:35:16.250
This star is based on the
bio-socioeconomic assessment,

00:35:16.250 --> 00:35:19.810
including stakeholder value, so
what they value in the fishery.

00:35:19.810 --> 00:35:21.770
This is giving us
different results,

00:35:21.770 --> 00:35:25.520
which I think means that we
need to look closer at this

00:35:25.520 --> 00:35:28.230
because perhaps we're
not even managing to what

00:35:28.230 --> 00:35:30.660
the majority of
stakeholders actually want.

00:35:30.660 --> 00:35:31.160
Right?

00:35:31.160 --> 00:35:33.110
This is a post-normal question.

00:35:33.110 --> 00:35:36.890
We have to get people around
the table using the philosopher

00:35:36.890 --> 00:35:39.731
Mary Parker Follett, who is
my favorite philosopher-- you

00:35:39.731 --> 00:35:40.480
should Google her.

00:35:40.480 --> 00:35:44.820
She's really, really cool-
she was born and raised

00:35:44.820 --> 00:35:46.930
in Massachusetts
in the late 1800s

00:35:46.930 --> 00:35:50.290
and did a lot of political
management theory

00:35:50.290 --> 00:35:52.550
and how to resolve conflicts.

00:35:52.550 --> 00:35:54.820
She says that, unless you
have diverse stakeholders

00:35:54.820 --> 00:35:59.350
around the table and they get
to reevaluate their objectives--

00:35:59.350 --> 00:36:01.664
so you have one
iteration of stakeholders

00:36:01.664 --> 00:36:02.830
and they say what they want.

00:36:02.830 --> 00:36:05.210
And then you do
that again and again

00:36:05.210 --> 00:36:07.450
and again until
they can realize,

00:36:07.450 --> 00:36:10.020
where is the integrated
solution going to come from?

00:36:10.020 --> 00:36:11.640
It has to come from us.

00:36:11.640 --> 00:36:13.600
How is it going to get there?

00:36:13.600 --> 00:36:19.910
So this is all towards the area
of the focus imaginarius, where

00:36:19.910 --> 00:36:21.490
we want to be.

00:36:21.490 --> 00:36:23.960
We have to start making
small steps to get there.

00:36:28.130 --> 00:36:31.550
So that's some work
that I have done

00:36:31.550 --> 00:36:34.510
and, I want to put it
also in a little bit

00:36:34.510 --> 00:36:36.110
different perspective as well.

00:36:36.110 --> 00:36:40.740
Let me kind of sum up
before I go to the part

00:36:40.740 --> 00:36:43.640
where I show you
some cool data stuff.

00:36:43.640 --> 00:36:46.130
This is kind of part of
the Occupy Science movement

00:36:46.130 --> 00:36:49.210
because I find a lot of
the scientific ethos being

00:36:49.210 --> 00:36:50.590
very important here.

00:36:50.590 --> 00:36:53.090
So I'm a biologist
and I collect data,

00:36:53.090 --> 00:36:56.140
but I understand that the
employment data in the fishery

00:36:56.140 --> 00:36:57.370
is really quite important.

00:36:57.370 --> 00:36:59.590
I understand the power
of the policymakers

00:36:59.590 --> 00:37:02.150
to put forward science.

00:37:02.150 --> 00:37:08.360
So I want to put this forward
as, how can we save the Ocean?

00:37:08.360 --> 00:37:10.420
Unless we educate
our students to see

00:37:10.420 --> 00:37:14.880
the Whole, the Whole
with the big W,

00:37:14.880 --> 00:37:17.070
they'll never understand
how their discipline,

00:37:17.070 --> 00:37:20.490
how their knowledge fits
into the whole, right?

00:37:20.490 --> 00:37:22.360
So this is getting
a little bit back,

00:37:22.360 --> 00:37:25.034
bridging the gap that we got
from the French Revolution.

00:37:25.034 --> 00:37:26.950
It's very good to have
disciplined scientists.

00:37:26.950 --> 00:37:28.010
That's great.

00:37:28.010 --> 00:37:28.880
This is technology.

00:37:28.880 --> 00:37:30.190
This is advancement.

00:37:30.190 --> 00:37:34.430
But we can't do that to the
expense of the grand challenges

00:37:34.430 --> 00:37:39.040
that we have-- climate change,
renewable resource management.

00:37:39.040 --> 00:37:41.830
Once they understand how
they fit into the whole,

00:37:41.830 --> 00:37:43.900
you can have cooperation
among disciplines

00:37:43.900 --> 00:37:47.740
to understand the whole and then
to use the data in integrated

00:37:47.740 --> 00:37:50.680
platforms in an extended peer
community-- this is relating

00:37:50.680 --> 00:37:52.850
to post-normal
science-- to inform

00:37:52.850 --> 00:37:56.288
science-driven policy not
policy-driven science.

00:37:58.980 --> 00:38:01.680
Again, this is a little bit of
the Occupy Science movement,

00:38:01.680 --> 00:38:04.590
where you have to stand
up for what science can do

00:38:04.590 --> 00:38:08.270
and what it can't do and
actually look at that.

00:38:08.270 --> 00:38:08.770
OK.

