00:38:38.840 --> 00:38:41.640
that we have on DNA
sequencing up in the cloud

00:38:41.640 --> 00:38:44.900
so people can access it, look
for new clues in the DNA,

00:38:44.900 --> 00:38:48.140
look for new-- if you're looking
for personalized medicine,

00:38:48.140 --> 00:38:49.250
all this type of thing.

00:38:49.250 --> 00:38:51.070
Where you have all
these public databases

00:38:51.070 --> 00:38:55.680
of data going into
the DNA Nexus cloud.

00:38:55.680 --> 00:38:57.590
Their office is
in Mountain View,

00:38:57.590 --> 00:39:01.069
so there's probably some people
who have maybe heard of this.

00:39:01.069 --> 00:39:03.360
So basically you're putting
everything up in the cloud,

00:39:03.360 --> 00:39:06.070
and you can use your
research community,

00:39:06.070 --> 00:39:08.250
for example, your biologists,
your statisticians,

00:39:08.250 --> 00:39:12.380
other collaborators, to
combine all of this data,

00:39:12.380 --> 00:39:14.190
look at different
analyses and get results

00:39:14.190 --> 00:39:17.520
that you couldn't have gotten
otherwise through a network.

00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:20.630
It's fascinating.

00:39:20.630 --> 00:39:23.200
It's really easy to see
how you would apply this

00:39:23.200 --> 00:39:27.380
to fish and oceans because
we only have one Ocean.

00:39:27.380 --> 00:39:29.560
That's why I have
Ocean with a capital O.

00:39:29.560 --> 00:39:32.540
And so everything is
inherently interconnected.

00:39:32.540 --> 00:39:34.450
We must remember that.

00:39:34.450 --> 00:39:37.140
This is an example
I was referring

00:39:37.140 --> 00:39:40.490
to ICES, the
International Council

00:39:40.490 --> 00:39:41.860
for the Exploration of the Sea.

00:39:41.860 --> 00:39:44.930
There's over 1,600 scientists
that routinely, every year,

00:39:44.930 --> 00:39:46.380
meet in working groups.

00:39:46.380 --> 00:39:51.210
This is an overview of some
of the data that they have.

00:39:51.210 --> 00:39:56.440
For example, they have
almost 700,000 measurements

00:39:56.440 --> 00:40:01.190
from the biological
community over 34 years.

00:40:01.190 --> 00:40:05.130
You have from the-- sorry.

00:40:05.130 --> 00:40:10.100
From the oceanographic data,
you have 245 million data points

00:40:10.100 --> 00:40:11.590
over 122 years.

00:40:11.590 --> 00:40:16.460
So we collect a lot of data
that's all publicly available.

00:40:16.460 --> 00:40:19.230
WWF has been doing
something really interesting

00:40:19.230 --> 00:40:19.960
in the Arctic.

00:40:19.960 --> 00:40:22.600
So this is a map of the Arctic.

00:40:22.600 --> 00:40:25.530
So here's Greenland.

00:40:25.530 --> 00:40:31.260
This is the eastern
coast of North America.

00:40:31.260 --> 00:40:32.140
And here's Iceland.

00:40:32.140 --> 00:40:35.270
Here's some data that they have.

00:40:35.270 --> 00:40:39.250
For example, you click
on a fish that you want,

00:40:39.250 --> 00:40:40.910
and this data is
actually showing

00:40:40.910 --> 00:40:45.450
all species and the relative
probabilities of occurrence

00:40:45.450 --> 00:40:46.990
in these areas.

00:40:46.990 --> 00:40:48.730
And so you have a
lot of different data

00:40:48.730 --> 00:40:51.487
that's kind of
overlayered each other.

00:40:51.487 --> 00:40:52.195
It's interesting.

00:40:55.460 --> 00:41:00.280
It's, for me, kind of
a toy to look around.

00:41:00.280 --> 00:41:03.217
It's not very, very
scientific, especially when

00:41:03.217 --> 00:41:05.550
you're talking about relative
probabilities, blah, blah,

00:41:05.550 --> 00:41:06.140
blah.

00:41:06.140 --> 00:41:10.069
But you can do it during
different seasons and all

00:41:10.069 --> 00:41:10.610
these things.

00:41:10.610 --> 00:41:12.870
And you can get a picture
of the fish that you want.

00:41:12.870 --> 00:41:14.530
It's really cool,
and it's showing

00:41:14.530 --> 00:41:16.950
that, unless we can
start mapping the Arctic,

00:41:16.950 --> 00:41:18.860
we can't really divvy
it up politically.

00:41:18.860 --> 00:41:20.480
We can't really study it.

00:41:20.480 --> 00:41:22.760
It's become a very big
political issue, for example,

00:41:22.760 --> 00:41:27.290
between Canada, USA,
Norway, and Russia.

00:41:27.290 --> 00:41:29.410
Who is going to own
these shipping lanes that

00:41:29.410 --> 00:41:31.980
are freeing up with the ice?

00:41:31.980 --> 00:41:36.850
Here's a paper that my
colleague, Nils Olav Handegard,

00:41:36.850 --> 00:41:38.880
published a couple
years ago, talking

00:41:38.880 --> 00:41:41.880
about how we're collecting data.

00:41:41.880 --> 00:41:47.080
This is a really cool thing that
the technology is there now.

00:41:47.080 --> 00:41:50.310
When we're at sea-- this is
our research boat, GO Sars.

00:41:50.310 --> 00:41:53.390
It's the world's most
advanced research vessel

00:41:53.390 --> 00:41:55.610
at my Institute of Marine
Research in Norway.

00:41:55.610 --> 00:42:00.960
We can see below, using acoustic
methods, what fish are there.

00:42:00.960 --> 00:42:02.450
And we can sample them.

00:42:02.450 --> 00:42:04.790
So we can match up
our acoustic sampling

00:42:04.790 --> 00:42:07.230
with the actual sample.

00:42:07.230 --> 00:42:10.750
For example, we can put these
sounders on cruise ships.

00:42:10.750 --> 00:42:16.440
So whenever they're going back
and forth for wherever they're

00:42:16.440 --> 00:42:18.350
going around the
world they can also

00:42:18.350 --> 00:42:20.480
be picking up continuous data.

00:42:20.480 --> 00:42:24.240
But Nils Olav has pioneered--
we have these missiles that they

00:42:24.240 --> 00:42:28.140
have in California,
which is really cool.

00:42:28.140 --> 00:42:30.000
They cost a lot.

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:32.500
They're multi-million
dollar little things,

00:42:32.500 --> 00:42:34.000
but you can shoot
them in the ocean,

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:36.190
and they just are
collecting data all over.

00:42:36.190 --> 00:42:38.940
There's people that spend
their whole careers on this.

00:42:38.940 --> 00:42:41.170
I'm not doing it
that much justice.

00:42:41.170 --> 00:42:43.260
But one thing that
Nils Olav has done

00:42:43.260 --> 00:42:48.240
are these sounders that are in
the sea bed of the floor that

00:42:48.240 --> 00:42:53.370
are collecting data 24/7,
data like salinity, turbidity,

00:42:53.370 --> 00:42:57.440
but also fish acoustics,
what schools are passing,

00:42:57.440 --> 00:42:59.320
species identification.

00:42:59.320 --> 00:43:00.980
The thing that is
bad about the ships

00:43:00.980 --> 00:43:04.066
is that the fish avoid
the ship's, right?

00:43:04.066 --> 00:43:05.440
They don't want
to get near them.

00:43:05.440 --> 00:43:06.154
They're loud.

00:43:06.154 --> 00:43:08.570
They're clunky, and they know
they're going to get caught.

00:43:08.570 --> 00:43:12.910
Whereas if you have these
passive data collectors,

00:43:12.910 --> 00:43:16.890
this is a really
good way to do it.

00:43:16.890 --> 00:43:20.910
The problem being, once we get
this data, how do we share it?

00:43:20.910 --> 00:43:22.660
Where's a common platform?

00:43:22.660 --> 00:43:24.340
We're really going
at collecting data.

00:43:24.340 --> 00:43:29.160
We're really bad about
sharing it and knowing

00:43:29.160 --> 00:43:32.460
how do we integrate it.

00:43:32.460 --> 00:43:34.930
So the Norwegian public
has paid for this.

00:43:34.930 --> 00:43:37.250
Why should they share it
with the rest of the world.

00:43:37.250 --> 00:43:39.240
So that's what we're
really missing is

00:43:39.240 --> 00:43:44.110
a common platform and people
who understand these data

00:43:44.110 --> 00:43:45.620
platforms.

00:43:45.620 --> 00:43:50.620
This is the last data
thing I want to show you.

00:43:50.620 --> 00:43:51.850
This is really cool data.

00:43:51.850 --> 00:43:54.030
This is, again, coming from WWF.

00:43:54.030 --> 00:43:57.110
This is data coming from
a single bluefin tuna.

00:43:57.110 --> 00:44:01.240
Bluefin tuna is the iconic
species, for me, of the Ocean.

00:44:01.240 --> 00:44:03.190
It's my favorite fish.

00:44:03.190 --> 00:44:06.180
It spawns in the Mediterranean,
crosses the Atlantic

00:44:06.180 --> 00:44:07.810
to the Caribbean
to start feeding up

00:44:07.810 --> 00:44:10.080
the eastern seaboard,
crosses again,

00:44:10.080 --> 00:44:12.500
and it's now up in Norway again.

00:44:12.500 --> 00:44:15.270
It has been an endangered
species for a while.

00:44:15.270 --> 00:44:20.650
Now, it has rebounded, partly
because of political measures,

00:44:20.650 --> 00:44:21.360
finally.

00:44:21.360 --> 00:44:23.530
They have stopped a
lot of the overfishing.

00:44:23.530 --> 00:44:25.630
So pretty soon it
might be OK again

00:44:25.630 --> 00:44:28.890
to eat bluefin tuna,
which is really cool.

00:44:28.890 --> 00:44:31.720
Anyway, bluefin tuna
is a fantastic swimmer.

00:44:31.720 --> 00:44:34.020
This is where they tagged--
so you can tag them.

00:44:34.020 --> 00:44:38.030
You can shoot a little
tag in its back.

00:44:38.030 --> 00:44:42.690
Kind of like I guess in Jaws
where they shoot a harpoon,

00:44:42.690 --> 00:44:44.880
but this is-- you just
shoot it like a dart.

00:44:44.880 --> 00:44:46.610
And this is in
the Mediterranean,

00:44:46.610 --> 00:44:50.300
Palma de Mallorca, off
the coast of Spain.

00:44:50.300 --> 00:44:52.250
And you start getting
all these pings

00:44:52.250 --> 00:44:53.910
about where it's actually going.

00:44:53.910 --> 00:44:56.350
And this red spot is
where it popped off.

00:44:56.350 --> 00:45:01.260
So this was data from, I
think, seven or eight days.

00:45:01.260 --> 00:45:02.620
And you can do this.

00:45:02.620 --> 00:45:04.910
There's all these
other cool things

00:45:04.910 --> 00:45:10.360
that you can do with the
data, the crux of it being,

00:45:10.360 --> 00:45:11.970
OK, where do we put the data?

00:45:11.970 --> 00:45:12.990
How do we access it?

00:45:12.990 --> 00:45:15.490
How do we make sure the right
people get access to this data

00:45:15.490 --> 00:45:19.520
to actually do something
meaningful with it?

00:45:19.520 --> 00:45:21.820
So if we go back
to our issue, how

00:45:21.820 --> 00:45:23.960
can we sustainably
manage the Ocean?

00:45:23.960 --> 00:45:28.150
I put forward the power of
data and the power of getting

00:45:28.150 --> 00:45:31.260
an extended peer community
around the table to not just

00:45:31.260 --> 00:45:33.690
talk about data but also
to talk about values

00:45:33.690 --> 00:45:36.050
because there's a difference
between science for science

00:45:36.050 --> 00:45:39.950
and science for policy,
occupying science so we know

00:45:39.950 --> 00:45:44.130
what science can actually
give us and what it can't.

00:45:44.130 --> 00:45:47.240
And I would open up
the floor if anybody

00:45:47.240 --> 00:45:48.760
has any questions or comments.

00:45:48.760 --> 00:45:51.510
And looking forward to
hearing what you think.

00:45:51.510 --> 00:45:53.030
Thanks a lot.

00:45:53.030 --> 00:45:54.990
[APPLAUSE]

00:46:00.387 --> 00:46:01.845
Is there anything
that was unclear?

00:46:01.845 --> 00:46:04.120
I could reiterate.

00:46:06.594 --> 00:46:08.344
AUDIENCE: I have a
question about that one

00:46:08.344 --> 00:46:11.575
chart that you showed with the
cod and another kind of fish

00:46:11.575 --> 00:46:13.563
and you had the
star and the circle.

00:46:13.563 --> 00:46:16.550
The circle was what
the current fishing is

00:46:16.550 --> 00:46:19.196
and the star-- that
was to represent

00:46:19.196 --> 00:46:21.656
what would satisfy
all stakeholders?

00:46:21.656 --> 00:46:23.624
And one thing I
didn't understand--

00:46:23.624 --> 00:46:28.399
so it was looking for basically
harvesting bigger fish.

00:46:28.399 --> 00:46:29.774
And I didn't quite
understand how

00:46:29.774 --> 00:46:31.520
that would satisfy
more stakeholders.

00:46:31.520 --> 00:46:34.860
DOROTHY DANKEL: Yeah, that
satisfies most stakeholders

00:46:34.860 --> 00:46:39.130
because the bigger the fish,
the more profit you receive.

00:46:39.130 --> 00:46:42.710
The bigger the fish,
the more you're

00:46:42.710 --> 00:46:45.410
waiting to fish
until they get big,

00:46:45.410 --> 00:46:48.417
which is preserving
the ecosystem.

00:46:48.417 --> 00:46:49.958
AUDIENCE: Does that
satisfy fishermen

00:46:49.958 --> 00:46:52.480
because that [INAUDIBLE]
means they would have to fish

00:46:52.480 --> 00:46:55.110
less now to wait for
these fish to get bigger.

00:46:55.110 --> 00:46:57.897
DOROTHY DANKEL: So there's a
different temporal time scales

00:46:57.897 --> 00:46:59.480
here, and there's
also the investment.

00:46:59.480 --> 00:47:01.590
So they've made
major investments

00:47:01.590 --> 00:47:05.350
to fish them at the current
size because to buy new nets

00:47:05.350 --> 00:47:08.870
and to change the net size
is a very large investment.

00:47:08.870 --> 00:47:11.700
So that shows that, in
this idealized world where

00:47:11.700 --> 00:47:14.279
they put preference on
profit, a little bit more

00:47:14.279 --> 00:47:16.320
in the industrial fishermen,
putting a little bit

00:47:16.320 --> 00:47:19.880
more preference on profit
than yield because there's

00:47:19.880 --> 00:47:21.897
a difference between
profit and catch.

00:47:21.897 --> 00:47:23.355
Because you can
get a lot of catch,

00:47:23.355 --> 00:47:26.940
but you could have used almost
all your resources to catch

00:47:26.940 --> 00:47:27.690
that catch.

00:47:27.690 --> 00:47:29.510
And the selling
price will be lower

00:47:29.510 --> 00:47:31.010
than what you actually put in.

00:47:31.010 --> 00:47:33.665
So if you focus on
profit, usually you

00:47:33.665 --> 00:47:37.030
have maximum profit before
you have maximum yield.

00:47:37.030 --> 00:47:40.520
So then if you focus on profit,
you're focusing on size.

00:47:44.330 --> 00:47:47.220
Especially if you talk about
tuna on the Japanese market,

00:47:47.220 --> 00:47:49.910
a bluefin tuna like this
is not worth anything.

00:47:49.910 --> 00:47:54.410
A bluefin tuna that's two meters
long could be worth $1 million.

00:47:54.410 --> 00:47:57.900
So there's a lot
of these dynamics

00:47:57.900 --> 00:48:00.000
that, until you start
modeling it and looking

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:01.070
at the trade-offs,
you don't really

00:48:01.070 --> 00:48:02.500
understand behavioral patterns.

00:48:02.500 --> 00:48:06.322
But if they put their
behavior and they want profit,

00:48:06.322 --> 00:48:08.405
you get different results
than if they want yield.

00:48:13.067 --> 00:48:14.400
It's different for each fishery.

00:48:14.400 --> 00:48:16.890
But in this case,
that was the case.

00:48:16.890 --> 00:48:17.686
Yeah?

00:48:17.686 --> 00:48:20.066
AUDIENCE: Did say something
about the difference

00:48:20.066 --> 00:48:22.684
between going around
and figuring out

00:48:22.684 --> 00:48:26.440
what everyone's interests are
and then doing all of this work

00:48:26.440 --> 00:48:29.880
to figure out what would be the
best thing versus getting them

00:48:29.880 --> 00:48:33.952
together to listen to each other
and figuring it out together?

00:48:33.952 --> 00:48:35.910
DOROTHY DANKEL: Yeah,
there's a big difference.

00:48:35.910 --> 00:48:39.560
So the philosopher I
mentioned, Mary Parker Follett,

00:48:39.560 --> 00:48:41.800
who I just think
is cool, she says

00:48:41.800 --> 00:48:46.460
that there's very different
psychological behaviors that

00:48:46.460 --> 00:48:47.190
are going on.

00:48:47.190 --> 00:48:50.750
If I'm a scientist, if I go to
everybody's office by myself

00:48:50.750 --> 00:48:52.000
and say, OK, what do you want?

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:52.930
Fill out this questionnaire?

00:48:52.930 --> 00:48:54.200
What do you want in the fishery?

00:48:54.200 --> 00:48:55.790
And I go to 20
different stakeholders

00:48:55.790 --> 00:48:59.740
and do that, combine that,
then I do the simulations,

00:48:59.740 --> 00:49:01.730
and I say, OK, this is
what you guys wanted.

00:49:01.730 --> 00:49:02.910
They see the results.

00:49:02.910 --> 00:49:06.840
They might say, eh, no I
didn't really mean that.

00:49:06.840 --> 00:49:08.940
In climate change
science, there's

00:49:08.940 --> 00:49:13.780
a big difference between the
preferences that they state,

00:49:13.780 --> 00:49:17.240
their stated preferences and
their revealed preferences.

00:49:17.240 --> 00:49:20.190
So I might say that I'm all
for helping climate change,

00:49:20.190 --> 00:49:23.510
but at the end of the day,
I'm still buying my tickets

00:49:23.510 --> 00:49:26.580
to San Francisco for
a three-day vacation

00:49:26.580 --> 00:49:29.540
because my revealed
preference is actually

00:49:29.540 --> 00:49:31.240
different than what I state.

00:49:31.240 --> 00:49:34.370
So it's important, she says,
to get people around the table

00:49:34.370 --> 00:49:37.060
and give them a chance to
reevaluate their positions

00:49:37.060 --> 00:49:39.770
according to the
positions of other people.

00:49:39.770 --> 00:49:41.600
So you get different
fishermen and say, OK,

00:49:41.600 --> 00:49:43.140
what do you want
out of the fishery?

00:49:43.140 --> 00:49:45.540
He says, I want to
catch a lot of fish.

00:49:45.540 --> 00:49:47.800
The next fisherman,
you ask him, he says,

00:49:47.800 --> 00:49:49.870
I want a 10% profit margin.

00:49:49.870 --> 00:49:53.320
And then the guy next to him
is like, oh, that sounds good.

00:49:53.320 --> 00:49:55.070
I think I want that too.

00:49:55.070 --> 00:49:55.635
Right?

00:49:55.635 --> 00:49:57.260
And then he's like,
so, as a scientist,

00:49:57.260 --> 00:49:59.210
what's the difference
between maximum yield

00:49:59.210 --> 00:50:01.580
and 10% profit
margin in my fishery?

00:50:01.580 --> 00:50:03.620
And I say actually
you would catch less.

00:50:03.620 --> 00:50:04.930
You would have more vacation.

00:50:04.930 --> 00:50:06.250
You would have more money.

00:50:06.250 --> 00:50:08.690
And then, all of a sudden, if
he had not been in the room

00:50:08.690 --> 00:50:10.770
when the other people
stated their preferences,

00:50:10.770 --> 00:50:12.810
he wouldn't see
different options.

00:50:12.810 --> 00:50:15.470
And you can't look for
integrated solutions

00:50:15.470 --> 00:50:19.390
unless those people are
there at the same time.

00:50:19.390 --> 00:50:21.310
AUDIENCE: So how do
you get them together?

00:50:21.310 --> 00:50:24.390
DOROTHY DANKEL: You get them
together through, for example,

00:50:24.390 --> 00:50:25.350
research projects.

00:50:25.350 --> 00:50:27.250
We have research
projects where we

00:50:27.250 --> 00:50:29.350
have stakeholder
consultation and stakeholder

00:50:29.350 --> 00:50:32.320
workshop, stakeholder
framing meetings.

00:50:32.320 --> 00:50:35.764
This has become really a la
mode in Europe at the moment.

00:50:35.764 --> 00:50:37.180
So I have a lot
of colleagues that

00:50:37.180 --> 00:50:40.680
get-- the European Commission is
paying for this type of science

00:50:40.680 --> 00:50:41.780
to be done.

00:50:41.780 --> 00:50:45.670
We still have to make the
bridge to actual politics

00:50:45.670 --> 00:50:51.080
and actual decision-making based
on these type of workshops.

00:50:51.080 --> 00:50:53.280
We're not there yet because
at the end of the day,

00:50:53.280 --> 00:50:55.380
it's still some
people in Brussels

00:50:55.380 --> 00:50:57.550
who are going to decide
what the fishing quota is

00:50:57.550 --> 00:50:59.700
and they do this
behind closed doors.

00:50:59.700 --> 00:51:04.290
So we have to get the show,
the methodology, in practice

00:51:04.290 --> 00:51:07.350
and really push hard for that.

00:51:07.350 --> 00:51:10.082
That's, I think, the
way you have to go.

00:51:10.082 --> 00:51:13.526
AUDIENCE: So how do you weight
stakeholders, some of whom

00:51:13.526 --> 00:51:15.494
are more important that others?

00:51:15.494 --> 00:51:18.446
The recreational fishermen
or the [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:27.310 --> 00:51:29.690
DOROTHY DANKEL: Yeah, so
this is a big question.

00:51:29.690 --> 00:51:31.150
This is where you go.

00:51:31.150 --> 00:51:33.495
I mean, this is a question
for political science,

00:51:33.495 --> 00:51:35.120
for anthropologists,
social scientists,

00:51:35.120 --> 00:51:37.770
who gets to sit at
the table, right?

00:51:37.770 --> 00:51:40.890
Because that's a big
commitment to sit at the table

00:51:40.890 --> 00:51:42.460
because if it's an
iterative process,

00:51:42.460 --> 00:51:46.240
you have to have the funds
to actually be there.

00:51:46.240 --> 00:51:49.480
You have to have knowledge
to actually participate.

00:51:49.480 --> 00:51:52.960
And it's a time and an
economic commitment.

00:51:52.960 --> 00:51:54.087
There's not one answer.

00:51:54.087 --> 00:51:55.170
It depends on the fishery.

00:51:55.170 --> 00:51:58.120
And, again, this is
a political question.

00:51:58.120 --> 00:51:58.920
Science can help.

00:51:58.920 --> 00:52:01.880
So science can, for
example-- social scientists

00:52:01.880 --> 00:52:04.350
can say who the main players
have been the last 10

00:52:04.350 --> 00:52:07.320
years based on their attendance
at different meetings,

00:52:07.320 --> 00:52:09.920
their profits coming from the
fishery, how many people they

00:52:09.920 --> 00:52:12.310
employee in the fishery,
and these types of things.

00:52:12.310 --> 00:52:17.030
But usually what's
done in Europe--

00:52:17.030 --> 00:52:18.790
we have the regional
advisory counsels,

00:52:18.790 --> 00:52:20.456
which is the meeting
of the stakeholders

00:52:20.456 --> 00:52:22.040
for the different
regions of Europe.

00:52:22.040 --> 00:52:25.580
They are I sign
up, and what we see

00:52:25.580 --> 00:52:28.370
is there's an overflow
of industrial fishermen

00:52:28.370 --> 00:52:31.530
and fisherman representatives
and not very many

00:52:31.530 --> 00:52:34.340
conservationists because
they're spread thin.

00:52:34.340 --> 00:52:36.320
They can't send
somebody to Copenhagen

00:52:36.320 --> 00:52:38.290
every six weeks to
have the meeting.

00:52:38.290 --> 00:52:43.460
So you don't see a
real democracy there.

00:52:43.460 --> 00:52:45.220
It's still the
people with the money

00:52:45.220 --> 00:52:47.440
who are participating
in the stakeholder.

00:52:47.440 --> 00:52:50.150
So that's a question
for democracy

00:52:50.150 --> 00:52:52.230
actually, as it should be.

00:52:55.209 --> 00:52:55.709
Yeah?

00:52:55.709 --> 00:52:57.530
AUDIENCE: So in
that chart that you

00:52:57.530 --> 00:53:02.170
showed where the star was
on the optimal fishing.

00:53:02.170 --> 00:53:05.152
That was 100% take
at a certain size.

00:53:05.152 --> 00:53:07.882
Is that in any way practical?

00:53:07.882 --> 00:53:09.340
DOROTHY DANKEL:
It's not quite 100%

00:53:09.340 --> 00:53:17.020
because-- the practicalities are
really disputable about that.

00:53:17.020 --> 00:53:20.050
It depends on the fishery.

00:53:20.050 --> 00:53:22.560
First of all, it
would take-- this

00:53:22.560 --> 00:53:24.910
is when you talk
about paradigm change.

00:53:24.910 --> 00:53:27.850
For the fishermen to wait until
the cod is this big to catch,

00:53:27.850 --> 00:53:30.730
it's not even on
the radar, right?

00:53:30.730 --> 00:53:33.980
They mature when
they're about this big.

00:53:33.980 --> 00:53:38.310
Science has shown that there's
tendencies for-- we're actually

00:53:38.310 --> 00:53:40.440
seeing the fish evolve
in front of our eyes.

00:53:40.440 --> 00:53:43.260
In the last 40
years, cod has been

00:53:43.260 --> 00:53:44.910
maturing at nine years of age.

00:53:44.910 --> 00:53:46.680
And now, because the
fishing mortality

00:53:46.680 --> 00:53:49.370
is many more times
the natural mortality,

00:53:49.370 --> 00:53:53.110
they're spawning
sooner because they

00:53:53.110 --> 00:53:54.720
know that they're
going to get caught.

00:53:54.720 --> 00:53:58.190
So now they're
spawning at five, six.

00:53:58.190 --> 00:53:59.200
So they're shrinking.

00:53:59.200 --> 00:54:00.570
It's a shrinking fish.

00:54:00.570 --> 00:54:02.330
This has ethical
considerations too

00:54:02.330 --> 00:54:07.230
because we're changing their
biology because of the fishing

00:54:07.230 --> 00:54:07.730
pressure.

00:54:07.730 --> 00:54:09.550
So it's not really on
the fishermen's radar

00:54:09.550 --> 00:54:13.790
to wait until they're this
big, even though, ecologically,

00:54:13.790 --> 00:54:16.570
and from a profit
standpoint, it could-- so,

00:54:16.570 --> 00:54:18.660
I mean, the practicalities
are up to debate.

00:54:18.660 --> 00:54:21.824
I presented this to
200 Norwegian fisherman

00:54:21.824 --> 00:54:24.970
and it wasn't
really on the radar.

00:54:24.970 --> 00:54:26.630
They understand the concept.

00:54:26.630 --> 00:54:28.980
And, again, that result.

00:54:28.980 --> 00:54:33.300
I don't put much trust
in that result, per se.

00:54:33.300 --> 00:54:38.060
We would have to do many more
different types of analysis

00:54:38.060 --> 00:54:41.160
to get some real
certainty of that, OK,

00:54:41.160 --> 00:54:44.060
can we trust this
somewhat or not.

00:54:44.060 --> 00:54:46.296
The fact of the matter is
that we have all the data.

00:54:46.296 --> 00:54:47.920
We just have to do
it, and this is just

00:54:47.920 --> 00:54:50.910
showing an outline of how you
can incorporate stakeholder

00:54:50.910 --> 00:54:53.280
utility functions and
look for strategies

00:54:53.280 --> 00:54:55.950
that satisfy as many people.

00:54:55.950 --> 00:54:59.810
So the practicalities
are up to the fishermen

00:54:59.810 --> 00:55:02.060
and what they're
willing to change

00:55:02.060 --> 00:55:04.430
and policymakers because,
at the end of the day,

00:55:04.430 --> 00:55:06.920
they have to put
objectives on the table.

00:55:06.920 --> 00:55:08.690
What are they actually
trying to achieve

00:55:08.690 --> 00:55:12.290
if they're going for
profitability, then,

00:55:12.290 --> 00:55:15.330
OK, we can show those trade-offs
for the other systems.

00:55:15.330 --> 00:55:18.430
But having a framework
where you can

00:55:18.430 --> 00:55:20.510
show trade-offs is
of utmost importance

00:55:20.510 --> 00:55:23.420
because that's what you have
to do, at the end of the day,

00:55:23.420 --> 00:55:26.200
is to make some decisions.

00:55:26.200 --> 00:55:27.990
Thanks a lot for having me.

00:55:27.990 --> 00:55:30.402
[APPLAUSE]

